From: python-wasm build
Subject: Make python.sh --version smoke test non-fatal

The cpython WASI build's final step runs `python.sh --version` to confirm
the build artifact loads. In our build, python.wasm has unsatisfied
component imports (the tegmentum:* multiplexers are plugged in later via
wac/composectl), so wasmtime errors before main runs. The build itself
succeeded — only the smoke check fails.

Convert the check_call to a try/except + warn, matching the equivalent
fix in 3.14's Tools/wasm/wasi/__main__.py.

diff --git a/Tools/wasm/wasi.py b/Tools/wasm/wasi.py
--- a/Tools/wasm/wasi.py
+++ b/Tools/wasm/wasi.py
@@ -276,7 +276,17 @@ def make_wasi_python(context, working_dir):
              quiet=context.quiet)

     exec_script = working_dir / "python.sh"
-    subprocess.check_call([exec_script, "--version"])
+    # The smoke check runs python.sh --version under wasmtime; if any
+    # component imports are unsatisfied (e.g. tegmentum:*-multiplexer is
+    # composed in later via wac/composectl), wasmtime errors. That's fine
+    # here — the wasm build itself succeeded, and Phase 1+ extensions
+    # deliberately leave unsatisfied imports. Make it non-fatal so the
+    # rest of the make chain (web-transpile, etc.) proceeds.
+    try:
+        subprocess.check_call([exec_script, "--version"])
+    except subprocess.CalledProcessError as e:
+        print(f"⚠️  smoke `python.sh --version` failed (rc={e.returncode}); "
+              "OK if python.wasm has unsatisfied component imports composed in later")


 def build_all(context):
